Jimmy, I really don't think you understand the situation for both Trump and 
Hillary. The establishment loves Hillary, and, unless it is all an act, the 
establishment hates Trump. So, however may you feel about Trump, his 
ascension is popular based, and all the backlash is coming from the 
Republican Party establishment. Clinton, on the other hand, has had the 
complete support of the establishment to the point of accusation of voter 
suppression coming from within the DNC. 

Now, look at the situation carefully. The Democratic voter numbers are low 
for a contested convention in some states 20 -30 percent drop-off, and the 
Republicans have had historic turnout in primary voting. If the numbers are 
indicator of Democratic Party turnout in the general election, then Clinton 
has real problem to overcome. And in this Democratic lull in voter turnout, 
you have to consider that Bernie's is the one generating any new 
enthusiasm, and most of the new votes are most likely attributed to his 
campaign. 

So again, you have to look at important factors - who hates these 
candidates. Well, Hillary is loved and admired by the establishment, and 
news media, however, the majority of the public has great disdain for HRC. 
Is Trump as universally disliked as Clinton? Maybe in California, or states 
with a large amount of Latino voters, but he'll dominate in state like 
Florida and Ohio, and in regions like Midwest and Deep South. Hillary has 
New York and California, but a region like New England might be a challenge 
for her to capture. 

This election is going to come down to a numbers game where Clinton has to 
bank on the lesser-of-two-evil voting. But is she really the lesser the 
lesser of two evils? And besides the popularity and ethical question about 
candidates are considered another factor has to be consider, while I rarely 
agree with Cenk analysis, I believe he's absolutely correct in his 
assumption that Trump will own Clinton in the debates. She only has PC type 
defense, and Trump is not going to care one little bit about any kind of 
political correctness. The media is going to exploit the sensationalism for 
all its worth, so Hillary is not going to get any mercy there - outside of 
MSNBC. 

So, besides Hillary's base, can she convince enough new voters to come out, 
in addition to getting Sanders voters that are not going to be swayed so 
easily to come out and vote for a candidate that Sanders has painted as a 
bought and controlled politician because even if Bernie's supports are 
added to Hillary's current base of devotees, HRC still comes up short.﻿
